<Author>CleoV
<Content>Terrible guest relations, filthy rooms, misrepresented We booked the Days Inn Civic Center Miami based on their website description and pictures, for a 5 night stay during Super Bowl week. Of primary importance to us was the availability of in-room internet access, as my husband is a sports writer and would need internet access throughout our stay.When we entered our room the first thing we noticed was water damage on the walls and ceiling and watery evidence on the carpets indicating the moisture problem was ongoing. The furnishings were old, worn and decidedly dirty. The bathroom was moldy and looked as if it had not been cleaned. We were willing to overlook these problems as we knew we had booked a relatively inexpensive hotel ($90 per night). However, after 20 minutes of frustration at trying to access the internet, we contacted the front office informing them there were no wireless connections within range. They told us to keep trying. We called again 10 minutes later, at which time they told us they would 'reboot' the system. 10 minutes later we called again and were told there was nothing they could do about it.We took our laptop and walked the property, looking for a wireless signal. The best signal we found was rated 'poor', and was right next to the lobby. Hoping for the best, we asked to be moved to a room closer to the lobby. Aleida at the front desk told us she would not move us to any of the several rooms we knew were empty (we saw them as we were walking the property). We had not used our room in any way, but she assured us nothing would change her mind and that we could check out if we didn't like it. We asked to speak to a manager and she refused, saying she was 'in charge now' and she wasn't going to call the manager. When we asked why she could not move us she said, 'Other people made reservations'. We reminded her we had also made a reservation for the exact room type we were asking to be moved to, and that our booking was based on the fact they advertised in-room wireless access. She told us we could sit in the lobby and pay for access using their computer if we wanted to use the internet.After many frustrating attempts at getting moved to a room that might have a wireless signal, and Aleida's smirking refusal to accommodate that request, we checked out of the hotel. Happily, we found a gorgous suite in South Beach for only $9 per night more than the horrible Days Inn Civic Center, so I suppose Aleida did us a favor. Her attitude convinced us this was not a hotel worth giving our money to, and I was truly relieved not to be spending even one night in that filthy room. Potential guests should be aware they may not get the services Days Inn's website claims are included, and if they are not happy with something about their room, well...in the words of Aleida, 'too bad! If you don't like it, check out.' I'm so glad we did. 
